[32m+[m[32m## Conclusion[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis capstone set out to prove something the other five projects in this[m
[32m+[m[32mportfolio only implied: that they add up to a single, coherent environment[m
[32m+[m[32mworth operating as one, not five disconnected exercises. That's genuinely[m
[32m+[m[32mdemonstrated here - a shared Log Analytics workspace pulling real telemetry[m
[32m+[m[32mfrom storage, Key Vault, Azure Automation, and Data Factory resources built[m
[32m+[m[32macross four earlier projects, queried through KQL that answers actual[m
[32m+[m[32moperational questions, and visualised in a Workbook that didn't exist until[m
[32m+[m[32mthis project connected the dots.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe build also surfaced one more real platform quirk to add to this[m
[32m+[m[32mportfolio's running list: `Get-AzAutomationAccount` doesn't expose a[m
[32m+[m[32m`.ResourceId` property on the installed module version, requiring the[m
[32m+[m[32mresource ID to be constructed manually from its component parts - the same[m
[32m+[m[32mcategory of SDK/module inconsistency that's shown up repeatedly across this[m
[32m+[m[32mbody of work, each time diagnosed properly rather than worked around blindly.[m
[32m+[m[32mThat diagnostic discipline is, at this point, as much the point of this[m
[32m+[m[32mportfolio as any individual Azure service.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mSeven projects, seven different angles - identity, cost, migration, data[m
[32m+[m[32mpipelines, backup and recovery, security posture and secrets, and now[m
[32m+[m[32mobservability tying the other six together - all built on a genuinely free[m
[32m+[m[32mAzure subscription, all documented with the real obstacles included rather[m
[32m+[m[32mthan edited out. That's the portfolio.[m
